  <body>
    <p>Given the recent advancements in CLIP-seq technologies and their broad applications, it is imperative to develop computational tools for the uniform processing and peak calling of CLIP-seq datasets. This work aims to provide a pipeline for the quality control and analysis of CLIP-seq data. This idea is not new. The only method innovation from this work is the construction of the project website (
<ext-link xlink:href="https://nf-co.re/clipseq" ext-link-type="uri">https://nf-co.re/clipseq</ext-link>) such that the usage of the pipeline is quite easy. As a summary, this work may add to the literature of computational tools of CLIP-seq data if the following concerns are clarified.</p>
    <p> Major concerns:</p>
    <p> CLIP-seq technologies include a variety of CLIP-seq experimental assays, including HITS-CLIP, PAR-CLIP, iCLIP and eCLIP. For each type of CLIP-seq assays, there have been several computational tools for the data quality control and peak calling, e.g., CIMS/PEAKachu/CLIPper/CTK/Piranha for HITS-CLIP related technologies (HITS-CLIP, BrdU-CLIP), PARalyzer/Mi-Clip/CTK/Piranha for PAR-CLIP, CITS/PureCLIP/CTK/Piranha for iCLIP related technologies (iCLIP, eCLIP, iCLAP, urea-iCLIP, 4sU-iCLIP, Fr-iCLIP), and CLIPper/CTK/Piranha for eCLIP. Notably, some of these tools are developed for a specific CLIP-seq assay, while some (e.g., Piranha and CTK) can be applied to different CLIP-seq assays.</p>
    <p> The authors may provide a more comprehensive introduction to the principles and characteristics for these existing computational tools in the main text.</p>
    <p> The authors may need to implement more computational tools (mentioned above) in their pipeline. More importantly, it should be made clear that which tool(s) could be used for which kind of CLIP-seq assay.</p>
    <p> Finally, the overlap of the peaks identified by using different tools from the same dataset should be shown in the main figure.</p>
    <p> Minor concerns:</p>
    <p> “e.g.” should be “e.g.,”</p>
    <p> “i.e.” should be “i.e.,”</p>
    <p>Are the conclusions about the tool and its performance adequately supported by the findings presented in the article?</p>
    <p>Partly</p>
    <p>Is the rationale for developing the new software tool clearly explained?</p>
    <p>Yes</p>
