  <body>
    <p>CLIP-based technologies produced lots of protein-RNA binding site data, which is important for RNA biology. However, an easy and better computational CLIP tool is still needed. The authors developed nf-core/CLIPseq-a robust Nextflow pipeline for quality control and analysis of CLIP sequencing data. They claim it is a best-practice, gold-standard set of pipelines for data analysis. It is really good and friendly for those people who is interested in RBP biology. My concern comments are the following.
<list list-type="order"><list-item><p>For peak-calling, what are the benchmarking results for PARpipe, Skipper, iCount, CLIP-Explorer, and other three peak callers (PEAKachu, Piranha, PureCLIP)? As a user, most researcher are caring about which peak callers is better?</p></list-item><list-item><p>The authors did a test run of 10 full-sized published iCLIP dataset (for the RBPs MATR3, PTBP1, STAU1 and TDP-43). What is the accuracy for these tools on different RBPs? The authors proposed three metrics to assess each peak calling tool and enable comparisons across them. So, what is the benchmarking result for comparison? What is the gold answer for each problem (for example, Peaker calling)? Could the authors rank these tools ?</p></list-item></list>
</p>
    <p>Are the conclusions about the tool and its performance adequately supported by the findings presented in the article?</p>
    <p>Partly</p>
    <p>Is the rationale for developing the new software tool clearly explained?</p>
    <p>Yes</p>
    <p>Is the description of the software tool technically sound?</p>
    <p>Yes</p>
    <p>Are sufficient details of the code, methods and analysis (if applicable) provided to allow replication of the software development and its use by others?</p>
    <p>Yes</p>
    <p>Is sufficient information provided to allow interpretation of the expected output datasets and any results generated using the tool?</p>
    <p>Partly</p>
    <p>Reviewer Expertise:</p>
    <p>RNA-binding protein,  RNA-protein interaction</p>
    <p>I confirm that I have read this submission and believe that I have an appropriate level of expertise to confirm that it is of an acceptable scientific standard, however I have significant reservations, as outlined above.</p>
  </body>
